Soft, made of potato, milk or cream (or sometimes lard), flour, cooked on a griddle.

Made of wheat flour typical of Oriya, Assamese and Bengali cuisine, dough is made by mixing fine maida flour with water and spoonful of ghee, then divided in small balls, flattened by rolling-pin, individually deep-fried in cooking oil or ghee, 4-5inches diameter, usually served with curries or gravies.

Pizza-like dough (flour, water, yeast, salt) kneaded well, risen, cut to large rounds, stretched, repeatedly warm ghee spread on dough as it is folded, round is stretched into flat round form, baked in tandoor-like oven.
Steamed, made of white flour, often slightly sweetened.
Belad Al Sham: Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Palestine
Usually large, round, about 2 feet, thin, almost translucent, dough is flattened, kept thin before cooking, baked on domed-convex metal griddle.
Kneaded, made with flour, salt, water, leavening.
Made of enriched dough covered in thin layer of crispy cookie dough.
Also known as rosetta, it has a hollow, bulging shape.
Also termed African coffee cake, golden crown, pinch-me cake and bubbleloaf; is a sticky, gooey pastry served as a breakfast treat.
Small, round, thin, usually dusted with cornmeal and served split horizontally, toasted, buttered, eaten as a snack alone or part of meal, usually breakfast or, in UK and Ireland, early-evening tea.
General term for leavened, oven-baked, typical of South and Central Asia.
Made of millet, water, vegetable oil.
Sweet dessert served for special occasions and festivals, stuffing of boiled chickpea lentils, turmeric, sugar, and spices, cooked on hot griddle, served with ghee and lentil broth soup.
Slightly sweet sandwich-style loaf with a dense crumb.
Sweet spongy, with ginger, honey, candied fruits, raisins, nuts, traditionally eaten around Christmas time.

Thin, flat, round cake, most are quick breads, some use a yeast raised or fermented batter, most are cooked on hot griddle or frying pan, one side first and flipped partway through to cook other side.
A rounded bread made of flour, eggs, yeast, sugar, and salt.

Traditional flatbread, thin, crisp, usually in form of a dish half a meter wide, made by taking baked Flatbread, splitting it in two sheets that are re-baked, recipe is ancient for shepherds who used to stay far from home for months, can last up to one year if kept dry.
Made from durum flour, often odd in shape.
White, distinguished by its shape and softness, made of several small sub-loaves or rolls to be broken off by hand, with oil added to dough, which makes it soft.

Fluffy, base round, octagon or star section, takes days to make to cure acidic dough like sourdough, contains candied citrus, raisins, sliced vertically, served with cider or champagne, esp. for Christmas, New Year.
Thin, crisp cracker-like, served with meal, as appetizer, as final item in meal, or as snack, eaten with various toppings: chopped onions, chutney, other dips and condiments.

Unleavened, made by pan frying whole wheat dough, ghee or cooking oil usually in dough and on done loaves, usually stuffed with vegetables or cheese, served with butter, chutney, spicy sauces or curries of meat and vegetables.

A parotta or barotta, is a common layered flatbread of Southern India. This is not to be confused with the North Indian Paratha. Parottas are usually available in restaurants and road side shops across Kerala, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu and the Middle East.
Made from sugar, butter, eggs, anise seeds and lemons.
Thin, usually made in Romagna region with white flour, lard or olive oil, salt, water, dough traditionally cooked on terracotta dish, today flat pans or electric griddles are more common.
Round with inner pocket, as it cooks, steam puffs up dough, as it cools and flattens a pocket is left in the middle.
Modern pizza was originally made with leavened wheat flour topped with tomato, now it also includes almost any other topping ingredients.
Round, made with milk, sugar or honey, subtly sweet lightly textured loaf, traditionally made for Christmas and Easter (when hard boiled eggs often baked in) times, today made year round.
Potato replaces part of normal wheat flour, ratio of potato to wheat varies much, leavened or unleavened, may have many other ingredients baked in, varied cooking methods.
Produced in a cast iron pot covered with wood coals, there are a wide range of flavours but is often made with wheat flour and sweetcorn.
An Alemannic knot-shaped bread, sometimes soft, sometimes hard, sometimes sweet, sometimes salty.
Small muffins or loaves of cornbread, was popular in times of widespread poverty, now is a common everyday meal.
Made from flour, salt, butter, milk, traditionally fried in animal fat, popular with children in winter.
Very heavy, dense, slightly sweet dark pure rye traditionally made with coarsely ground flour, now often made with mixed flour and whole grain berries.

Unleavened, made of wheat flour (refined, whole-wheat, or coarse), dough of flour and salt rolled into small circle or bigger and cut into small circles, deep fried in ghee or vegetable oil, puffs up in all directions like a round ball from steam inside.
Leavened with substance other than yeast.
Unleavened, made from stone ground wholemeal flour, traditionally named atta flour.

Made of rye and wheat flour or up to 1/3 whole rye grains may have whole seeds, usual sourdough base, low fat, no oil or flavoring but salt, high fiber, little or no sugar, usually long brown rectangle.
Made of various fractions of rye grain flour, color light to dark via flour used and if colors added, usually denser and higher fiber than many common breads, darker color, stronger flavor.
General term, used in Christian Eucharist ritual.
Made of wheat flour, starter of liquid (water or milk), either corn, potatoes, or wheat, and some other minor ingredients; result has dense crumb and positive cheese-like flavor.
Plain, rectangular, or triangular, whole wheat sourdough, usually two types: generic no toppings and costlier topped with poppy or sesame seeds.
Small quick bread usually made of wheat, barley or oatmeal, baking powder leavening.
Cut into strips, fried and salted.
Saffron-flavored traditional flatbread, usually made with milk instead of water.

A variety of quick bread traditionally made in a variety of cuisines in which sodium bicarbonate (otherwise known as baking soda) is used as a raising agent rather than the more common yeast. The ingredients of traditional soda bread are flour, bread soda, salt, and buttermilk. The buttermilk in the dough contains lactic acid, which reacts with the baking soda to form tiny bubbles of carbon dioxide. Other ingredients can be added such as raisins, egg or various nuts.
A kind of fried pastry and a type of quick bread.
A rye pancake made between two iron plates, filled with lard or bacon, dried sausage and a little syrup .
Leavened flour bread with saffron and small amount of cardamom powder baked in a clay oven.
Any kind of cake that is sturdy enough to be picked up with the fingers.

Rice paste bread made with sesame oil and with a pattern baked into the top made by painting rice paste onto the surface prior to baking. The paste dries and cracks during the baking process, creating a two-colour effect similar to a tiger's markings, hence the name.
A sweet bread formed of braided strands of dough and may also be savoury.
Soft (used as wrap for other food), or crisp (used with fermented herring), many variants depending on type of grain (any mix of wheat, barley, rye), leavening agent (or lack), and rolling pin.

A bread baked traditionally at Christmastime. It is rich in eggs and butter, making it similar to brioche. Lemon rind and nutmeg add color and flavor; the dough can also contain raisins and almonds, and is braided like challah.

A type of bread that is produced from a process developed in Vienna, Austria, in the 19th century. The Vienna process in part used high milling of Hungarian grain, cereal press-yeast for leavening, and care and thought in the production process.
Bread made from wheat flour from which the bran and the germ have been removed through a process known as milling.
A type of bread that is made using flour which is partly or entirely made from whole or almost whole wheat grains, see whole wheat flour and whole grain.
Thin, round, unleavened, similar to lavash, about 18inches (40–50cm) wide, usually made of wheat flour, water, table salt, has low moisture content, depending on how low this is, a long shelf life.
A type of crisp, sweetened bread, made with eggs and baked twice. It is sliced before it is baked a second time, which produces crisp, brittle slices that closely resemble melba toast.

data: After waking up in the Village and discovering his captivity there, Number Six encounters a friend from the outside who may have a possible escape.
A new prisoner, Nadia, may have information about the Village that makes an escape attempt possible.
A desperate Number Two tampers with Number Six's dreams to discover where his loyalties lie.
Presented with the opportunity, Number Six runs for election to the post of Number Two.
Number Two replaces Number Six with a duplicate to weaken the real Six's sense of identity.
An important prisoner's new speed-teaching machine poses perhaps the greatest threat to Number Six's independence.
After waking to find the Village deserted, Number Six returns to England but does not know whom he can trust there.
Number Six tries to save an old friend headed for destruction at the hands of the Village.
Number Six thinks he has a means to tell the prisoners from the wardens.
Number Six takes revenge on a sadistic Number Two for the death of another prisoner.
To save the prisoner who is being set up to take the fall, Number Six must intervene in a Village power struggle and prevent the assassination of a Number Two.
Number Two stirs the Village to ostracize Number Six, and then takes even more drastic measures to cure Six's "unmutuality".
[Do_Not_Forsake_Me_Oh_My_Darling|Do Not Forsake Me Oh My Darling]
In an Old West setting, a lawman who resigned is trapped in a town called Harmony where the Judge wants him to be the new sheriff — by hook or by crook.
Number Six avoids the assassination attempts of a beautiful woman while foiling the plots of her megalomaniac father.
Number Two subjects Number Six to a desperate, last-ditch effort to subdue him, Degree Absolute — an ordeal that will not end until it breaks one of them.
Number Six encounters the forces behind the Village, but can he finally escape?

table-0204-62.caption: References
data: Located southeast of the intersection of 2080 E and 1200 N.
Defunct. The original location is on a hill Northeast of the intersection of 3050 N and 1730 E which is just West of Alvin.
Located at the east edge of Kickapoo State Park, this cemetery was dedicated in 1864 and deeded from Sylvester and Martha Hutton.
Located on the southeast edge of Danville and was started in 1858 on landed deeded by the grandfather of Paul Atherton. It is located on Lewis Road, to the south of New Atherton Cemetery (see below).
Located in the churchyard of the Free Methodist Church. Stones here date from the 1880s.
Located in the northwest corner of the township.

Jeremiah Brittingham came to Vermilion County in 1830 from Ohio and died in the winter of 1831; due to the extreme cold, he could not be buried immediately. An Indian chief died shortly thereafter and his people asked that he be buried with Jeremiah.
Located north of the grade school in Westville, established on land provided by Joshua and Charles Caraway, which they acquired in 1824.
Sometimes known as Milner Cemetery, it is next to Milner School.
Colliers Cemetery is also sometimes called Humrick Cemetery and is just south of the small town of Humrick.
Adjacent to the Songer Cemetery, this cemetery contains the graves of many residents of the Vermilion County Home.
Named for John Cox who was born in 1799, was a scout in the Black Hawk War, and settled in the Middle Fork area in 1829. It is within Kickapoo State Park.

data: 22-year-old Svendsen took his first WC victory after being one of three to complete the race without penalties. Svendsen started early, and by the time he finished, the seeded group were still at the second or third shoots. 23-year-old Sednev scored his first WC podium, beating fellow Ukrainian Berezhnoy, who would also have been a first-time podium visitor, by 0.3 seconds. Ukraine, like Germany, had three men in the Top 10.

22-year-old Svendsen took his first WC victory after being one of three to complete the race without penalties. Svendsen started early, and by the time he finished, the seeded group were still at the second or third shoots. 23-year-old Sednev scored his first WC podium, beating fellow Ukrainian Berezhnoy, who would also have been a first-time podium visitor, by 0.3 seconds. Ukraine, like Germany, had three men in the Top 10.

24-year-old Youriyeva became the second biathlete of the day to notch up a career first WC victory. It did not look that way throughout, as she trailed Magdalena Neuner by 50 seconds after two loops, with the German having completed three shoots without mistake. However, Neuner encountered fierce winds on the final standing shoot, missing four times and crashing to seventh.

24-year-old Youriyeva became the second biathlete of the day to notch up a career first WC victory. It did not look that way throughout, as she trailed Magdalena Neuner by 50 seconds after two loops, with the German having completed three shoots without mistake. However, Neuner encountered fierce winds on the final standing shoot, missing four times and crashing to seventh.

Simon Fourcade led after the standing shoot, having hit 10 targets, ahead of Nilsson, Yaroshenko, Aidarov and Bjørndalen. However, Bjørndalen rallied with the fastest final lap, beating Yaroshenko by 13 seconds to snatch victory and have the Sprint Cup lead for himself. Nilsson managed to beat Fourcade in the final lap, taking his first podium for two seasons.

Simon Fourcade led after the standing shoot, having hit 10 targets, ahead of Nilsson, Yaroshenko, Aidarov and Bjørndalen. However, Bjørndalen rallied with the fastest final lap, beating Yaroshenko by 13 seconds to snatch victory and have the Sprint Cup lead for himself. Nilsson managed to beat Fourcade in the final lap, taking his first podium for two seasons.

Bailly scored her third victory of the season, and Mäkäräinen entered the WC podium for the first time in her career. They both missed one target, while the race's fastest skier, Neuner, despite missing three shots, managed to get the third podium place. She was the only one of the Top 10 that had three misses; no Top 10'ers shot perfectly. Bailly took over the Sprint Cup lead from Kati Wilhelm, who came in 18th with three penalties. Glagow kept her yellow bib.

Bailly scored her third victory of the season, and Mäkäräinen entered the WC podium for the first time in her career. They both missed one target, while the race's fastest skier, Neuner, despite missing three shots, managed to get the third podium place. She was the only one of the Top 10 that had three misses; no Top 10'ers shot perfectly. Bailly took over the Sprint Cup lead from Kati Wilhelm, who came in 18th with three penalties. Glagow kept her yellow bib.

Russia won with the biggest separation from the second place in the season. Germany used seven spare rounds more in standing that did not save her from the penalty loop. Austria has engaged to 8 spare rounds in both prone and standing shooting to finish third. At the shooting range Hanevold and Bjørndalen repeated results of Kruglov and Yaroshenko in the previous relay race, making Norway the fourth.
